node.text:
Industrial Revolutions has just turned 10 years old 🥳.

Myself and @stu_thomson created the film back in 2011 for a really cool Channel 4 documentary called “Concrete Circus” which was concerned by the brilliant @mikechristieuk .

The ideal for the documentary was to get together 4 different athletes from 4 different “action sports” disciplines who had all had some kind of success making a viral film on YouTube which was fairly new at the time. 

I teamed up with my good pal @stu_thomson who had been making cool mountain bike content for years and had just changed the name of his production company from MtbCut to @cutmedia .

With a bit of Googling for abandoned places, we came across Dunaskin Ironworks which was a cool old railway yard in south west Scotland. 

Once we got there we realised we had totally lucked out with the location and how many in interesting relatable featured it had! From old trains sat on old rusty train tracks to old building missing their roofs.

My favourite feature though had to be an old Crane that had its boom stretching across to another carriage with a flat roof giving me the opportunity to try and ride/wobble along the it’s rusty  cable! 

We set about trying to film 2 to 3 lines a day over a period of 6 days all captured on Stu’s trusty Cannon 5D which definitely wasn’t easy. But with the help Nash Masson @ridescotland and @monobartlett we gradually ticked off the different lines and tricks.

Music is also such an important part of our films and it can take me weeks to find the right track.  For Industrial 
Revolutions though a friend who was working at universal sent over some tracks from some new artists he had on the label. Luckily for us @benhoward_ was in that list with his track “Wolves” which hadn’t been released yet. The vibe and lyrics ended up fitting perfectly with our wee film so thanks again to Ben and his label for letting us use it!

All in all we are really chuffed with how the film turned out and for us it was really cool to be part of the Concrete Circus  documentary along side all the other amazing athletes and filmers. 

Here’s to another decade of making films 🍻

#industialrevolutions #bikes #trains #trials

Got peer pressured into riding this log on the heckler while the @monolith.css crew were building the coarse for @krisskyle’s awesome “Out Of Season” film! 

🎥 @jakewalters_ 

#emtb #northshore #wales

Throwback to climbing up the “Inaccessible Pinnacle” on the Isle of Skye’s Cuillin Ridge with my bike, while filming in 2014 for the @cutmedia film “The Ridge” .

We couldn’t have been any luckier with the weather that day, with the clouds whisping over the top of the ridge.  It was an amazing feeling standing up there taking in the views of my home Island and knowing it was all getting captured on film using tech that’s was fairly new at the time (a drone) flown by the awesome @mrleccorp to show to folk around the world just how cool a place it is!

Highly recommend getting up there to see it for yourself with @skyeadventure as a guide but don’t recommend doing it with your bike!

#theridge #isleofskye #scotland #mountainbiking #gopro

📸 @darkskymedia 🙌

node.text:
This is me practicing “Hippie Hops” before filming one for my @xgames real mtb part. 

Using hazard tape is the best way to learn them as it breaks when you catch your feet. It’s also easier to see is space to get your timing right on the running up.

Definitely worth giving them a try as they are a wee bit easier than they look once you commit!

#mountainbiking #hippiehop #realmtb

Running has never been my strong point 🏃 😂 

Crashing on the other hand….

🎥 @jakewalters_ 

#runningman #Klinsmann #frontflip #crash #xgames

node.text:
Industrial Revolutions has just turned 10 years old 🥳.

Myself and @stu_thomson created the film back in 2011 for a really cool Channel 4 documentary called “Concrete Circus” which was concerned by the brilliant @mikechristieuk .

The ideal for the documentary was to get together 4 different athletes from 4 different “action sports” disciplines who had all had some kind of success making a viral film on YouTube which was fairly new at the time. 

I teamed up with my good pal @stu_thomson who had been making cool mountain bike content for years and had just changed the name of his production company from MtbCut to @cutmedia .

With a bit of Googling for abandoned places, we came across Dunaskin Ironworks which was a cool old railway yard in south west Scotland. 

Once we got there we realised we had totally lucked out with the location and how many in interesting relatable featured it had! From old trains sat on old rusty train tracks to old building missing their roofs.

My favourite feature though had to be an old Crane that had its boom stretching across to another carriage with a flat roof giving me the opportunity to try and ride/wobble along the it’s rusty  cable! 

We set about trying to film 2 to 3 lines a day over a period of 6 days all captured on Stu’s trusty Cannon 5D which definitely wasn’t easy. But with the help Nash Masson @ridescotland and @monobartlett we gradually ticked off the different lines and tricks.

Music is also such an important part of our films and it can take me weeks to find the right track.  For Industrial 
Revolutions though a friend who was working at universal sent over some tracks from some new artists he had on the label. Luckily for us @benhoward_ was in that list with his track “Wolves” which hadn’t been released yet. The vibe and lyrics ended up fitting perfectly with our wee film so thanks again to Ben and his label for letting us use it!

All in all we are really chuffed with how the film turned out and for us it was really cool to be part of the Concrete Circus  documentary along side all the other amazing athletes and filmers. 

Here’s to another decade of making films 🍻

#industialrevolutions #bikes #trains #trials

This is my most comedy crash from 2020.  We were out filming for our @enduraofficial film “This and That” when at the end of a long days filming I decided to try and nose bonk a tree stump next to a trail.  In my typical fashion, I half asses my first attempt and overshot to stump, leaving me to nose dive onto the trail and fly out of control into the bushes.  Luckily there wasn’t anything nasty waiting to get me in there and I came of unscathed!

🎥 @robbie_meade @wearepeny
